    "id": 225,
    "url": "/how-youtube-can-improve-its-customer-service-solution-so-that-both-the-company-and-its-customers-are-better-off/",
    "title": "How YouTube can improve its customer service solution so that both the company and its customers are better off",
    "body": "2022/03/20 - In a previous postI complained about YouTube depriving me and many other users of access to its video sharing and streaming service simply because we deleted our unused account. At the time of this writing, I’m still stuck in thisuncomfortable situation like many others. My access to YouTube. com hasn’t been stored, and I still can’t find a way to contact YouTube’s representatives to have this issue addressed. Engineering is supposed to makethings easy. Deleting data shouldn’t take this long. In this blog post, I’d like to share from my point ofvideo how YouTube can improve its customer service so that both the business and its customers like you andme can better off in situations like this. YouTube has grown rapidly into a global video sharing service with thousands and millions of users consuminginformation from YouTube on a daily basis worldwide. YouTube was acquired by Google in the last decade and had since expanding across multiple disciplines and markets. Just like other Google services, YouTube has an official help centre where users come to find solutions to their concerns with YouTube’s products. To manage such a huge customer base, YouTube’s help centre incorporates modern technologies to make it as smartas possible. Hiring hundreds of people responding to similar questions related to YouTube isn’t cost effective. From my experience, the help centre is designed to be autonomous, meaning that it requires as less time fromYouTube’s staff as possible. The help centre has a search bar. When users type in their questions, the search tool will generate a list of threads from help forums posted by other users, prompting users to search for answers from existing threads. Whilst this setup can free up a lot of time from YouTube’s employees, it’s troublesome in some rare cases like mine. Since removing my channel with no original uploads, likes, or comments, with just six playlists built from videos uploaded by other users and a hundred subscriptions, I’ve been locked out from YouTube account. WheneverI try to sign in to YouTube with my Google account, it always displays an error page with a message saying thatI can’t sign in while my data is being deleted. I understand that data deletion can take some time as I’m a web developer myself. However, after one hour, three days, now an entire week, I start to get more irritating as I continue tobe blocked out from the largest video community in the world for doing nothing in violation of YouTube’s policiesor anything wrong or unethical. This puts me - and users who’re in similar situations - in a very uncomfortableplace. I search all over the Web for solutions to fix this problem. I see many threads online complaining about the sameissue. The oldest post was made in 2015. There’re more recent posts as well. There’re countless complaints on thisbug on Quora, Reddit, and YouTube’s very own help forum. None of these included a solution - either from users who suffered from this nonsense or from representatives at YouTube. So I visited YouTube’s help centre in hope toget in touch with some customer support specialists. The help centre, whether you start with the search bar on the front page or click through contact options, you’re always prompted to enter your question in a wizard, and that wizard will always pop up some close threads related tothe issue. All of them are authored by users, and none of them offered a solution. There isn’t a way to hold a live cchat with a customer service representitive or write an email to YouTube to report the issue. I’m not even a professionalYouTuber. Just imagine how frustrated would be for YouTubers and businesses that rely on the site for a living when they’re put through this chaos. I believe there’re many ways for YouTube to improve its customer support solution so that everyone – both the companyand its customers – will better off. I think YouTube’s current strategy is working. An automated help centre is a fit fororganisations of YouTube’s size. However, there’re many details that YouTube can refashion and refine. First, YouTube should do more work to make its help centre effective. Rather than pointing users to a list of threads,YouTube should develop mechanisms to rate the quality of the threads and solutions offered in these threads. Threads withoutaccepted solutions should remain open to new input whether or not they’re active. I see a dozen thread on YouTube complainingabout exactly the same problem. This shouldn’t have happened. It’s frustrating to click and read through all the posts. This is time-consuming and ineffective. YouTube should aggregate the threads, use algorithms or manual labour to combinethreads on same topics. Stack Overflow – the professional developer community – has been doing a fabulous job at this. When users visit the centre, they expect to get their answers as quickly and effortlessly as possible. Who doesn’t want tosave their precious time? By combining threads, users can find relevant content much easier. Second, replies to thread questions that offer no value should be removed after some time. It makes no sense to repeat what others have said. I’ve seen in many of the threads many users are simply replicating thecomplaints.    “Yes, I encountered the same issue. Please help!”     “I don’t know what’s happening, I’ve been looking all over the place and still find no clue…”  Posts like these add little to no value to the help forum threads. These should be removed either periodically or after a solutionhas been identified and accepted. Online customer service is much more than providing a place for customers to vant. It shouldput customers at the centre and help them achieve their objectives. It shouldn’t stop untile customer demands are fulfilled. Third, there should be a human service option somewhere. YouTube simply can’t and shouldn’t rely upon automation to serveits customers. Whilst the wizards are in one way or another effective in addressing users’ concerns, not all issues can be addressedin the user community without engagement with corporate representatives. Afterall, YouTube is the provider who created the service,no one knows better about YouTube than YouTube. Some months ago, I had a problem with my Autodesk account. Autodesk is another prominent software provider with offerings that include some of the most widely used industrial design software solutions such as Fusion and AutoCad. The customer service from Autodesk was far more superior than that of YouTube. Whilst I wasn’t able to log into my account, I was able to hold a livechat with company representatives who very patiently analyse my issue, walked me through some solutions, provided me an email address to follow up on the problem, and, after everything failed, the representative handed me over to another specialist to assist me until I successfully fixed the problem. This is what quality customer service should look like. It’s approachable, charming, andeffective. In the case of YouTube, I don’t feel like I’m being treated fairly. There really isn’t a customer service. My recommendation would be for YouTube to rate the threads and solutions using either an algorithmatic solution orhuman service specialist. If a thread contains a working solution, then the wizard should prompt the user to view that thread first. If the user concludes that the thread isn’t helping, there should be a place for the user to provide feedback by rating the thread and solution. Then, YouTube should encourage the user to offer more details by creating a new thread and inviting some real human representatives from YouTube to participate in the thread or hold a live chart or have some back and forth email communications to help address issues. YouTube may also collect customer feedback on their service to understand customers demands and expectations better. Help forums shoud include not only inputs from users but also inputs from YouTube. I believe by making these changes, both YouTube and its customers can be better off. YouTube can maintain a good reputation and higher quality service while customers can have their concerns effective addressed. These are all I have come up with as of now. I will update this article to include more solutions for YouTube to make its customer service better. "
