    "url": "/business-analytics-vs-computer-science-who-wins-the-final-round/",
    "title": "Business Analytics VS Computer Science - Who Wins the Final Round?",
    "body": "2021/05/20 - In a previous post (the “Post”), I discussed my path forward after graduating college. While I was certain about pursuing a master’s degree for the sake of career advancement, I was undecisive between business analytics and computer science. In this article, I would like to extend on that conversation to try reach a conclusion. Business analytics is a business school program. Considering my background in finance and information systems, business analytics appears to be a better choice than computer science because it integrates analytical and technical skills. In business analytics, not only you learn to perform technical tasks, but also to interpret the results, which is arguably, more important than number crunching itself. Therefore, I decided to consider business analytics an option. Computer science, on the other hand, is an art and science program. Some universities also categorize computer science as an engineering discipline. Unlike business analytics, this is what I call a “purely technical” degree. That is, computer science puts much heavier emphasis on technology than business analytics. In business analytics, you learn a lot about business including marketing, management, and accounting in addition to SQL, R, and Python; however, in computer science, you spend all the time learning operating systems, programming languages, and algorithms. I fell in love with technology since the first time I code in an information systems class. I was so passionate about technology; therefore, I also consider computer science an option. After consulting with my professors, the internet, and my parents and asking myself “what do I want to achieve” for a few times, I have decided to pursue computer science. As mentioned in the Post about the difference between the Chinese and American job markets, Chinese companies tend to favour “technologists with business knowledge” but not “analysts with technical know-how”. China is an emerging economy. It is growing faster than the rest of the world. This means it is more likely to encounter issues in China ahead of other countries. These issues present challenges but also opportunities. Having spent four years in the United States, while I appreciate the American ideal of freedom of speech and so on, China is where the future lies. I strongly believe in China’s potential – not because it is my home country, but it is a fact that even Western powers cannot deny. Thus, to prepare for my transition back into the Chinese economy, I must equip myself with a solid technical foundation. After spending four years at a business school, I believe I already have the managerial and analytical mindset necessary to be successful in business. Conclusively, I will spend the next couple of months, even years, to prepare for my graduatelevel education in computer science. Since I come from a business background, I received much less technical training than computer science undergraduates even though I majored in information systems. Therefore, I expect to see obstacles on my journey ahead, but I will not and cannot afford to back down because computer science is the way to go. I must be prepared to do whatever it takes to achieve this goal. This is imperative because after leaving college, I will be the only driver of myself. I must motivate myself to act and not only to think about the future. In the next post in this series, I will discuss what I plan to do to prepare for a graduate-level education in computer technology. "
    }, {
    "id": 289,
    "url": "/communication-is-the-solution-to-people-issues/",
    "title": "Communication is the Solution to People Issues",
    "body": "2020/12/29 - You probably have heard of it many times that communication is the answer to most problems in a collaborative environment. As an information systems student, I learned this through projects in a hard way. I believe successes and failures all deserve reflections. They should be openly discussed. In this article, I want to share my thoughts on communication based on my project experience. In the summer of 2020, I agreed to help a friend who had little to no web development experience to build a website for a client based in Atherton, California. I agreed to do so for two reasons – first, he was my best friend at that time; and second, I wanted to put my coding skills into practice. With COVID-19 spreading rapidly across the states in the summer, we collaborated on Teams throughout the process. Obviously, I learned a lot from that project, but I want to concentrate on communication in this article because we had some serious communication-related issues. I learned three lessons. Lesson 1: Make a plan but expect it to run off tracks Every project requires a plan for team members to work closely and keep moving forward. However, it is critical to expect that things may not go as planned, which is usually the case. As the only team member with the necessary technical competencies, I played a pivotal role that essentially managed all aspects of the website. While I was assigned to build back-end applications to collect and analyze data, I was forced to write some front-end code as well because my friend was still learning to code, and he made quite a lot of mistakes…usually the same ones. I was frustrated because that was not how we planned. I got to work extra hours but received the same paycheck. I reflected on what happened. It is true that things fell apart, but – Is it a surprise that as the only technician on the team I got to work longer hours? Is it my friend’s fault to have repeated the same mistakes as a beginner in web development? The answers are no. So, what went wrong? Nothing went wrong but communication. Instead of bringing up our feelings on team meetings, we chose to keep them to ourselves, which did not help remove negativities but helped them grow. Eventually, they exploded and adversely impacted the team’s progress. We ended up blaming each other based our own perspectives – I complained about how he repeated those mistakes based on the assumption that we should follow the plan, and he is able to pick up front-end skills as quickly as I did, and he blamed me for not offering enough help based on the assumption that just because I am more technically capable, he could leave all those code issues for me to fix. That is not how things should have worked. Instead of keeping these negativities to ourselves, we should have openly discussed them. The only way to fix these issues is communication. We were not supposed to keep those feelings private because of the fear that these negativities may ruin the cooperation. In fact, those issues are part of our cooperation. If I face this issue again, I will bring it up as soon as possible so it does not stick with the team. Lesson 2: Always communicate with the goal of fixing problems instead of just throwing out personal feelings We oftentimes draw an equal sign between communication and expression, but from my perspective, that is not the case. We want to express our feelings through communication, but communication should not stop there. We must understand that other people are not trash cans for holding negativities. When we have concerns, we should raise them up and fix them. The goal of communication should always be fixing problems instead of shooting negativities at others. I learned this from the project as well. When the negativities exploded, we started badmouthing. I labeled him as a web rookie and blamed me as a loose cannon. We expressed our feelings, but there was no sincere and constructive communication. We did not realize it for a while, and those blame games solved no issues at all. In hindsight, we could have done much better by expressing our feelings, expecting others would not immediately accept those perspectives, and trying to fix the issues and stop them for good through constructive communication. Communication goes beyond expression to address issues. Lesson 3: Expect to communicate multiple times Communication is a lasting process. We should not expect to solve problems with only one or two chats. Instead, we should expect to communicate repeatedly. While this sounds annoying, it is necessary. This is the third lesson I learned from that project. We are not controllers of other people’s minds, so we should expect the result of communication to be different from what we expected. While our goal is to deliver the favorable result, it may not come with first few rounds of communication. It is crucial to understand problem solving does not require imposition of one-sided perspectives. It is an exchange process because every person on the team is unique and has something different from yours. When you communicate, make sure that the goal is to solve issues, not necessarily persuading others to buy in your opinions. I think these lessons are helpful for me and for you all as well. This is the reason I decide to publish this article on my person website’s blog channel. You can read my other articles as well. I hope you enjoy this content. If you’re interested, you can visit https://www. christine4council2020. com/. This is the website we helped to build. I will see you in the next post. "
    }];

var idx = lunr(function () {
    this.ref('id')
    this.field('title')
    this.field('body')

    documents.forEach(function (doc) {
        this.add(doc)
    }, this)
});
function lunr_search(term) {
    document.getElementById('lunrsearchresults').innerHTML = '<ul></ul>';
    if(term) {
        document.getElementById('lunrsearchresults').innerHTML = "<p>Search results for '" + term + "'</p>" + document.getElementById('lunrsearchresults').innerHTML;
        //put results on the screen.
        var results = idx.search(term);
        if(results.length>0){
            //console.log(idx.search(term));
            //if results
            for (var i = 0; i < results.length; i++) {
                // more statements
                var ref = results[i]['ref'];
                var url = documents[ref]['url'];
                var title = documents[ref]['title'];
                var body = documents[ref]['body'].substring(0,160)+'...';
                document.querySelectorAll('#lunrsearchresults ul')[0].innerHTML = document.querySelectorAll('#lunrsearchresults ul')[0].innerHTML + "<li class='lunrsearchresult'><a href='" + url + "'><span class='title'>" + title + "</span><br /><span class='body'>"+ body +"</span><br /><span class='url'>"+ url +"</span></a></li>";
            }
        } else {
            document.querySelectorAll('#lunrsearchresults ul')[0].innerHTML = "<li class='lunrsearchresult'>No results found...</li>";
        }
    }
    return false;
}
</script>
<style>
    #lunrsearchresults {padding-top: 0.2rem;}
    .lunrsearchresult {padding-bottom: 1rem;}
    .lunrsearchresult .title {color: #d9230f;}
    .lunrsearchresult .url {color: silver;}
    .lunrsearchresult a {display: block; color: #777;}
    .lunrsearchresult a:hover, .lunrsearchresult a:focus {text-decoration: none;}
    .lunrsearchresult a:hover .title {text-decoration: underline;}
</style>


<form onsubmit="return lunr_search(document.getElementById('lunrsearch').value);">
    <p><input type="text" class="form-control" id="lunrsearch" name="q" maxlength="255" value="" placeholder="Search pages and articles across the website via Lunr.js" /></p>
</form>
